Customer LifeTime Value Prediction

Team 7

  • Amal, Jerome, Brinda, Akhil, Nancy, Tonmoy

What is Customer Lifetime Value Prediction?

Customer lifetime value (CLV or customer LTV) is the predicted sum total of all future revenues (or profits) that a particular customer will generate for a business. It can also be described as a measure of a customers total worth to a business over the entire time period of the customer-business relationship. By developing strategies to reduce client churn, policy term businesses can increase the overall CLV of its clients. Higher retention also leads to lower costs and better profit margins as retaining existing customers often costs less than acquiring new ones. Using accurate estimates of CLV as the basis for marketing decisions will maximize the companys revenues (or profits).

CLV = ((Average Sales * Purchase Frequency)/Churn)*Profit Margin.

Where, Average Sales = (Total Sales)/(Total no. of orders)

Purchase Frequency = (Total no. of orders)/(Total unique customers)

Retention Rate: (Total no. of orders greater than 1)/(Total unique customers)

Churn = 1-Retention Rate

Profit Margin= Based on Business Context.

EDA

A series of statistical tests will be done to understand the relationships between the features, but they are only supportive and not conclusive. The main insights come from the EDA

Customer

There are 9134 rows in the dataset and each of those rows correspond to a unique customer Id.

## [1] 9134

Customer Lifetime Value

There are 8041 unique CLV values distributed amongst 9134 customers. Meaning that about 12% of the customers share the same CLV value. Could the reason they share the same value be that they shared key properties when the CLV was originally calculated and therefore whatever formula/method was used to calculate CLV produced the same value? It could also be purely conincidental. On investigating the numeric column furthur it was found that it contains values with a minimum of 7 significant figures and minimum value of about 1898 and a max of about 83325, with a at least 1 and at most 13 digits after the decimal point as seen above. Could all those digits have matched by chance? Below are all the rows that share a particular CLV value.

As it can be seen, the customers are essentially the exact same in all columns but State, Policy type and Policy and their id. This pattern is followed for all the rows that share the same CLV. If the State values were erroneously entered, these could all be the same customer that bought different policies at the same time, which would imply that the CLV is independent of these values for a given person. Will need to investigate furthur. Below is the distribution of CLV. Its a highly positively skewed distribution, hence the following analyses will use the log transformed clv instead only for visualization. For the tests we use the original column. The data seems to consist of three clusters of points each having distinct CLV distributions. Divided about the median, all points having greater CLV seem to follow a positively skewed distribution and all points below the median seem to follow two different approximately normal distributions. These can be seen below for the CLV ranges of 1000-3000, 3000-5780 and 5780-90000 ### Response
This is the column that records the response of the customers to a renewal offer. This can be treated as a nominal variable. 

## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
## # A tibble: 2 x 5
##   Response count  mean    sd median
##   <chr>    <int> <dbl> <dbl>  <dbl>
## 1 No        7826 8030. 6969.  5814.
## 2 Yes       1308 7855. 6256.  5596.

Clearly, the assumption of normality is violated. Also since the sample sizes are not approximately equal, the t statistic will be skewed in the same direction as shown by the smaller sample. Will need a non-parametric test. Therefore proceeding with Mann-Whitney U test.

## 
##  Wilcoxon rank sum test with continuity correction
## 
## data:  Customer.Lifetime.Value by Response
## W = 5175420, p-value = 0.5169
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is not equal to 0

From above we can conclude that at 0.05 level of significance (The same level will be used in all the future tests), we fail to reject the null hypothesis that there is no statistically significant difference between the levels of response and therefore they are drawn from the same population. Hence knowing the response of a customer will not provide any new information on the values of the target. Moving onto the next variable,

State

State is a nominal variable and consists of the west coast states in the U.S., California, Oregon, Arizona, Nevada and Washington. 

## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
## # A tibble: 5 x 5
##   State      count  mean    sd median
##   <chr>      <int> <dbl> <dbl>  <dbl>
## 1 Arizona     1703 7861. 6703.  5791.
## 2 California  3150 8004. 6726.  5871.
## 3 Nevada       882 8057. 7092.  5630.
## 4 Oregon      2601 8078. 6909.  5906.
## 5 Washington   798 8021. 7410.  5502.

Normality is violated. Therefore we need to use the non-parametric equivalent of one-way ANOVA, the Kruskal-Wallis test. One of the assumptions of this test is homoscedasticity of the groups. In order to verify this, well need to use Levenes test:

## Warning in leveneTest.default(y = y, group = group, ...): group coerced to
## factor.
## Levene's Test for Homogeneity of Variance (center = median)
##         Df F value Pr(>F)
## group    4  0.6421 0.6324
##       9129

Thus from the p-value above we conclude that at a significance level of 0.05, we fail to reject the null hypothesis that all population variances are equal. This is also corroborated by the variances of the levels seen above. Having proved that the levels are homoscedastic we now move onto Kruskal-Wallis test:

## 
##  Kruskal-Wallis rank sum test
## 
## data:  Customer.Lifetime.Value by State
## Kruskal-Wallis chi-squared = 5.0721, df = 4, p-value = 0.28

As the p-value is greater than the significance level, we can thus conclude that there is no significant difference between the states, in terms of the CLV.

Coverage

About 61% of the cutomers chose the basic coverage while only 9% chose the premium coverage type. Of those customers that chose the premium coverage type, 73% had a CLV greater than the median CLV of 5780. Of those cutomers that chose the basic coverage type, 40% had a CLV greater than the median CLV. Finally of those with extended coverage type, about 62% have a value greater than the CLV median. Coverage could be used as an ordinal variable with the order of: Basic<Extended<Premium

## Warning in leveneTest.default(y = y, group = group, ...): group coerced to
## factor.

## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

This means that the null hypothesis of the equality of variances is rejected at the significance level. This being an assumption of Kruskal-Wallis, we wont be able to use it.

Income

As shown, it appears that unemployed people have a wide range of CLV, which is counterintuitive. In fact the distributions of both the groups are similar.

The majority proportions and the medians were found of the no income group. Some of them are: - 57% are single
- 60% opted basic coverage
- 34% went to high school or below
- 50% were male
- 524.836298 was the median total claim amount
- 91% responded no to a renewal offer
- 91% reside in a suburban area
- 79% had zero unsolved complaints
- 50% insured a four-door car.
In the group that had a non-zero income, all the above proportions and the medians are exactly similar expect that 53% resided in a suburban area and the median total claim amount was 340.8

Converting the categorical features to factors

When you make a categorical variable a factor, R creates dummy variables that represent each of the possible states, for example when gender is made a factor it encodes as male and female and individually estimates a coefficient for the effect of each.Making a variable into a factor treats it as nominal feature which means it does not consider the options as being ordered in any way.so the working is similar to that of one hot encoding.

Outliers:

An outlier is a point that has an extreme outcome variable value. The presence of outliers may affect the interpretation of the model, because it increases the RSE.

Outliers can be identified by examining the standardized residual (or studentized residual), which is the residual divided by its estimated standard error. Standardized residuals can be interpreted as the number of standard errors away from the regression line.

MAPE

The use of the MAPE as a loss function for regression analysis is feasible both on a practical point of view and on a theoretical one, since the existence of an optimal model and the consistency of the empirical risk minimization can be proved. Problems can occur when calculating the MAPE value with a series of small denominators.

## [1] 0.0118322

Residuals vs Fitted. Used to check the linear relationship assumptions. A horizontal line, without distinct patterns is an indication for a linear relationship, what is good. Normal Q-Q. Used to examine whether the residuals are normally distributed. Its good if residuals points follow the straight dashed line Scale-Location (or Spread-Location). Used to check the homogeneity of variance of the residuals (homoscedasticity). Horizontal line with equally spread points is a good indication of homoscedasticity. This is not the case in our example, where we have a heteroscedasticity problem Residuals vs Leverage. Used to identify influential cases, that is extreme values that might influence the regression results when included or excluded from the analysis. This plot will be described further in the next sections.

Ideally, the residual plot will show no fitted pattern. That is, the red line should be approximately horizontal at zero. The presence of a pattern may indicate a problem with some aspect of the linear model.

This plot shows if residuals are spread equally along the ranges of predictors. Its good if you see a horizontal line with equally spread points.like that of above.

The QQ plot of residuals can be used to visually check the normality assumption. The normal probability plot of residuals should approximately follow a straight line.

High leverage points:

A data point has high leverage, if it has extreme predictor x values. This can be detected by examining the leverage statistic or the hat-value. A value of this statistic above 2(p + 1)/n indicates an observation with high leverage (P. Bruce and Bruce 2017); where, p is the number of predictors and n is the number of observations.

Influential values An influential value is a value, which inclusion or exclusion can alter the results of the regression analysis. Such a value is associated with a large residual.

The Residuals vs Leverage plot can help us to find influential observations if any. On this plot, outlying values are generally located at the upper right corner or at the lower right corner. Those spots are the places where data points can be influential against a regression line.

When data points have high Cooks distance scores and are to the upper or lower right of the leverage plot, they have leverage meaning they are influential to the regression results. The regression results will be altered if we exclude those cases.

Assumpation Testing of Linear Regression Analysis

1.Multicollinearity

Checking correlation between independent variables.Variance inflation factor (VIF) is a measure of the amount of multicollinearity in a set of multiple regression variables.vif should be less than 3, here vif all the variables are less than 3 it fails to reject the null hypothesis .There is no multicollinearity

2.Autocorrelation

Null Hypothesis - There is no correlation among residuals.

Alternate hypothesis - Residuals are autocorrelated.

This is done Durbin-Watson Test If D-W Statistic is around 2, then we have autocorrelation in model. and away from 2 means no autocorrelation.

##  lag Autocorrelation D-W Statistic p-value
##    1      0.02701474      1.945968   0.024
##  Alternative hypothesis: rho != 0

P value is greater than .05 .We reject the alternative hypothesis ,So there is no autocorrelation

3.Heteroscedasticity:

Breuch- Pegon test:It is used to test for heteroskedasticity in a linear regression model. It test whether variance of errors from a regression is dependent on the values of a independent variable.

Null Hypothesis - Heteroskedasticity is present in Residuals.

Alternate hypothesis - Heteroskedasticity is not present in residuals.

## 
##  studentized Breusch-Pagan test
## 
## data:  model7
## BP = 2956.2, df = 25, p-value < 2.2e-16

A p-Value > 0.05 indicates that the null hypothesis(the variance is unchanging in the residual) can be rejected and therefore heteroscedasticity exists. This can be confirmed by running a global validation of linear model assumptions (gvlma) on the lm object.P should be on higher side.Here p is very low, reject null hypothesis. Heteroscedasticity is there

4.Normality:

Null Hypothesis - The residuals do not follow a normal distribution.

Alternate hypothesis - The residuals follow a normal distribution.

Anderson Darling test can be used for that

## 
##  Anderson-Darling normality test
## 
## data:  model7$residuals
## A = 869.33, p-value < 2.2e-16

P-value : The residuals do not follow a normal distribution (Reject H0).P value should be on higher side .But here P is very less. Errors are not normally distributed

What we done here is that on observing that the distribution of the dependent variable was a combination of three normal distributions we divided the dependent variable into three and made three linear regression models for each and then all three models have very high r square and adjusted r squared. The reason can be that seperating customers into three groups is like based on CLTV is like a short cut to customer segmentation. Although we split the model into three and produced good scores. Choosing the right model for unseen data might introduce error. Thats the drawback of the model. However, more than 73% of those that have premium coverage have CLV more than the median. And more than 60% of basic coverage has a CLV below the median. Also luxury car and luxury suv exclusively only CLV more than the medain. These facts can be used to pick the right model. combining the above three models which have high r squared approximately we will have to use ensemble techniques which is outside the scope of this project.

Conclusion

This report considered the problem of predicting customer lifetime value (CLV) of cutomers for an automobile insurance firm using linear models. CLV is a measure of the total profit a business can make from the entire lifetime of the relationship with a customer (lifetime being defined as the time period since the start of the relationship till the time the customer moves onto a competitor) Being able to predict/model this is very useful for businesses to help them considerablly reduce the costs of customer aquisition and provide more customer oriented services so as to increase profts. Being able to tell in advance which customer/ group of customers will stay loyal to your business will go a great way in at least maintaining the health of the business. Since CLV is usually calculated using RFM model or the formula, we could have made better models if we had data directly linked to the calculation of CLV such as on the frequency of the claims, customers claim amount, the interest rate, frequency of claims, etc.
